definition.value: Sexual stimulation or gratification of the self.
Note that this definition of masturbation does not include acts of mutual masturbation.
Masturbation performed mentally, i.e. without physical genital stimulation.

A term usually used to refer to a castrated person assigned male at birth (depending on the exact person they may or may not have had a male gender identity). Notably though, some sources simply used the term to refer to palace officials who may or may not have been castrated males. Alternatively used to refer to modern persons who identify as eunuchs.

In modern language, this term should be avoided whenever possible because it is unclear what is being referred to and can be construed as offensive under certain circumstances. However, the term can be appropriately applied in historical contexts.
Curiosity of a sexual nature or curiousity about sexual topics.

Curiousity about sexual intercourse of other experiences with persons of a gender that would constitute a person's implied sexuality being bisexual (for example, a gay man being curious about sex with a woman or a heterosexual woman being curious about sex with another woman).
A person who is cisgender and heterosexual.
Dysmenorrhea that occurs without an associated underlying condition.
A pale purple color, like that of the lavender flower. Lavender become symbol of homosexuality in the 1950s and 1960s, just as the color mauve was in the 1890s.

Any of various kinds of cross-dressing or construction of queerness within the context of performance. Generally used to describe men dressing as women (usually referred to as drag queens) or women dressing as men (usually referred to as drag kings), although this level of specificity has been the site of controversy for many LGBTQIA+ people.
Note that not all types of drag involve cross-dressing (i.e. drag queens who are trans women or drag kings who are trans men).
Dysmenorrhea that has a specific underlying cause, typically a condition that affects the uterus or other reproductive organs.
A significant pattern of gender dysphoria or other incongruence between one's gender identity and one's sexual characteristics.
A state in which life expectancy between populations is equalized as much as possible despite differences in demographics, such as gender, race, ethnicity, and socioeconomic status.
The state of being unequal; difference.
An adult person who is transgender.
A transgender person who is a veteran.
A transgender person who is part of and/or is employed by the military.
The time of life between childhood and maturity. This period overlaps with adolescence.

Transgender youth are children and adolescents who are transgender and/or transsexual. Because transgender youth are usually dependent on their parents for care, shelter, financial support, and other needs, and because most doctors are reluctant to provide medical treatments to them, transgender youth face different challenges compared to adults.
A young person who is transgender or otherwise gender nonconforming.

label.value: United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland

definition.value: A sovereign state established by the Acts of Union 1800, which merged the kingdoms of Great Britain and Ireland.

A state established in 1922 under the Anglo-Irish Treaty of December 1921. That treaty ended the three-year Irish War of Independence between the forces of the self-proclaimed Irish Republic, the Irish Republican Army (IRA), and British Crown forces.

A sovereign state in western Europe from 1 May 1707 to 1 January 1801. The state came into being following the Treaty of Union in 1706, ratified by the Acts of Union 1707, which united the kingdoms of England (which included Wales) and Scotland to form a single kingdom encompassing the whole island of Great Britain and its outlying islands, with the exception of the Isle of Man and the Channel Islands. The unitary state was governed by a single parliament and government that was based in Westminster.
